PROGRESS IS NOT LINEAR

Sure, if every variable is exactly the same day to day, linear progression could happen.

However, life doesn’t work that way- I’m speaking biologically and physiologically. 

Ladies, our hormones cycle every freaking month (this is only one variable) and that means we will fluctuate on the scale regardless of how consistent and strict we are simply because we are women and alive.

Gents (and ladies too) there are factors such as the amount of damage you’ve done to your muscles during a workout- inflammation to repair those muscles will increase water retention to heal and repair, therefore growing muscle mass. #agoodthing 

Salt intake, water intake, food intake, stress, sleep, etc etc etc etc ALL play a roll in your weight loss, weight gain and weight maintenance.

This is exactly why depending solely on the scale for your progress is pointless and worthless in the big picture.

Helpful: 
At home/nutrition focus on habits rather than numbers. Focus on drinking water, sleeping more/better, colorful plates, sitting down to eat, etc.

At the gym: focus on consistency, find a coach to program you based on your goals, history, abilities and then make it a habit to get that program accomplished. 
Here we can focus more on numbers: how much ya lifting’, how far ya runnin’, how high ya jumpin’. Focus on those numbered accomplishments here.

The scale is a tool (did I hydrate well enough yesterday, is my period around the corner type info) not a mark of how “fit” or “fat” you are.

Chasing the scale will leave you still wanting the body you see in the magazines…

This is not my forte.

Cardio of any sort never has been.
I’ve done body building, powerlifting. I ran in high school and would snowboard all day without stopping. But this is a different kind of appreciable pain. 

I’ve been wavering back and forth on a goal for a while now.  And I think I’m pretty ok with this #goal:

Feel good. 

I want to enjoy my workouts again because they challenge me, they aren’t mind numbing and I get results
I want to keep up and not be the liability.

As I get older what works for me changes. 
And I’m not always happy about  it; But here I am.
More super sets, sprints on the bike, less rest, more sweat. Less BB work, more challenge.

That will change as I progress but right now I’m getting my feet wet with the added cardio components. 

It’s ok to change, to not be defined by what you like to do in the gym.

It’s ok to be the worst in the room, as long as you’re working toward being the best.

Choose to do the Hard Things

Allowing things to haphazardly happen is a great way to stress yourself out and lose control of the mission.

Choosing to do the things that are difficult, not enjoyable and perhaps chaotic develops character, commitment and increases likelihood of reaching the goal.

Do the hard things on purpose:
The difficult exercise.
Cold plunging.
The sprints.
The better food choice.
Extra sleep.
Or maybe it’s NOT doing the thing you want to do (working out due to injury perhaps 😉).

Do the hard things because they matter. 
Do the hard things to develop yourself.
Do the hard things because they become easier when you do them again and again. 

You got this!

Is it the smartest thing I’ve ever done? No

Would I have a client do this? Once I perfect the angles, sure. 

Don’t do shit because you see it on IG. 
DO experiment and try somethings, sometimes, to keep moving forward.

Be smart (safe words?).
Have an exit strategy as best you can (what if this fails?).
Realize that just because it looks “interesting” doesn’t mean it’s safe, effective or worth the effort from here on out.

The angle here was less than ideal to achieve the effect I was looking for (cable pull needed to be more vertical than horizontal to be effective enough to try again). The potential injury factor (stepping onto the bench while loaded, was not ideal or even necessarily safe once the load I wanted would be strapped around my hips). 

Just because someone does it in the gym (can we please stop squatting on BOSU balls? Please and thank you) doesn’t mean it’s something you should try.

Think before you do. 

Remember: basics done consistently and progressively (load,reps, sets) will continue to be more effective than pulling some bullshit move just do look “different”.

If you can make “different work”, cool, go for it, but be Uber cautious and work smarter, not harder.

There is no one way…

…to get “fit”. There are a number of programs, philosophies and techniques to incur a benefit for general fitness. It’s more about general movement than achieving a specific goal. 

The more specific your goals, the more specific your programming, technique, consistency and path should be.

Even in that capacity you can get specific in very different ways and achieve those goals.

Connecting with a good coach who listens, isn’t a one trick pony and actually cares about helping you achieve what you’re wanting is a great place to start. 

My current goals are a mixture of things and to achieve those goals I am not working off of a strict program.  I have a general outline of my week’s training sessions and can play around within those parameters as I see fit.  However, that doesn’t give me leeway to be a lazy fuck. 
Regardless of the goals you will have to push yourself past your comfort zone to get much meaningful progress.

Don’t buy into hype used to sell programs (and yes you can make progress off of cookie-cutter programs). If someone says “this will be easy” they are a #lyingponydog 

Keys to successful programming:

1️⃣You should enjoy it enough to be consistent.  That’s not to say you’ll love every session, but you shouldn’t hate every minutes of every session.

2️⃣It should be geared in a direction to get you to your goals or be very specific to you, depending on the specificity of your goals.  Less specific = Less Specific. More = More.

3️⃣It should challenge you 80-90% of the time.  The extra 10% is just good for you (think Low Intensity Steady State work, or LISS).

4️⃣Assuming you’re consistent for long enough to see results, it should start to elicit the changes you are desiring.

Actually yes. You can.

But if you really want to know why you see it as an uphill battle, why you keep stopping, why you feel you can’t:

You’re not committed.

Commit and see what happens.
Commit and break through some plateaus.
Commit and stop whining about what you can’t do… start to focus on what you CAN do.

It’s not that hard. You just lack the commitment.

It’s a hard truth, but it is truth. Do with it what you will.

It’s time

To stop listening to the gym bros who have an ego to stroke. The ladies who think cardio is the only way.
The “I used to bench 748lbs in grade school” fellas. 

Ladies- wanna lift? Do it! 

Wanna bench? You got my full support.

Wanna grapple? Oh hells yes! 
 
Stop listening to the bros who have an opinion about everything they know nothing about.

Do the things that make you better, stronger, faster, happier. Do the things that make sense to YOU. The bystanders in the gym are simply that- bystanders. 

They are there for them, so be here for you!

Competing. 

I can’t count the number of women who have come to me over the years wanting to ‘get in shape’. I love it!
But one things the majority of them add onto that conversation is:  maybe compete.

Although I think its a nice motivation for some,  I don’t think it has any place in a ‘get in shape’ mindset.

Competing is not something you do to ‘get in shape’. It’s something you do because you’ve reached the point in your fitness journey that you need something to challenge you, to fulfill you because you love this lifestyle and want to be the best of the best.

This is a hard truth:  it’s really not for everyone.  Just because you workout and look the part doesn’t mean that you need to compete.  It’s not a requisite to being ‘fit’.

So if you feel that competing is a goal you have to have if you want to start a fitness journey, please reconsider.  You truly want to compete?  Cool, I will 100% support your goals and choice to do so.  But don’t think it will cure any part of what’s missing or broken in your mindset about working out if you’re just coming back to the fold.

Competing looks like: 
GYM is your priority.
FOOD (or lack thereof) is your priority.
COLD (drop in thermogenesis, BF, important bodily functions).
CRANKY / LACK OF SLEEP.
POST SHOW BLUES (it’s real and it sucks).
BEING HUNGRY.
A SLOWER METABOLIC RATE (watch those weeks post show or you’re in for another round of ‘get back in shape’). 

Feeling like a beast.  Being proud of yourself.
Fitting into clothes you couldn’t before (word of caution:  do NOT throw away clothes that are slightly too big for you at the time of your prep - you will need to buy those sizes again, trust me).

This is all to say:  you do NOT have to compete just because you want to ‘get in shape’.

PROTIP

Deadlifts & RDL’s:

Keep your upper body tight and quiet.

These are lower, hip and hammy dominant and the only thing your upper body is required to do is get and maintain rigidity & hold the load.
That’s it.

Shrugging is an energy leak. 

Grip, hold, engage hips/glutes and hams, dig heels into the floor, push your hips into the bar.
Think of pulling BACK, not up. 
🔥🔥🔥

Rep Ranges:

Max strength: 1-2/set
Power: 1-3/set
Strength: 4-8/set
Hypertrophy/size: 8-12/set
Endurance: 12+/set

These are general guidelines, not black and white.

Use numbers and principals as guides.
Keep in mind you are unique and what works well for one person may or may not work as well for you… 
then again, it may work better.

Keep your approach flexible and you’ll do great things!

Deadbugs

If you’re chatting with your friend, trainer or feel like Deadbugs are pretty easy…  YOU’RE NOT DOING DEADBUGS 

This isolation exercise should have you winded at the end of 30seconds. 

So if you’re able to go minutes in this position, here’s a cue/trick that may help you get the most out of your time:

Lay on a thicker pad or place a folded towel under your butt.  Scoot down until you feel your tailbone dip to the floor.  Now, get into your dead bug position but try to keep your tailbone OFF the floor. 
To do this, you’ll want to think of your knees reaching for the ceiling.  Your fingertips should be reaching to the ceiling as well and yes your chin will pull up  into your chest as your shoulders come off the floor slightly (think of a rolled towel under your neck).

While doing these things, your low back should be pressed into the floor and you should feel your abs bracing (think about someone about to punch you in the stomach and you ‘brace’ to lower the impact to your internal organs).
The trick to the deadbug hold is keeping this tension throughout your trunk for an extended amount of time- good luck!

This video is 30seconds of a deadbug.  I was winded and shaking by the time it was done (this is the 4th set). 

If your workouts don’t feel like you’re working your ass off to some degree, are you even working out?  Pull back, reevaluate form/technique and practice getting better at all your lifts - big and accessories alike. 

Doing things well and correctly pays off immensely on the journey to achieving your fitness goals.

Bulgarian Split Squat Variation

Here’s a simple tweak to your BSS that can make a big impact. Listen up athletes, weekend warriors or anyone workin’ on their fitnAss.

With the kettlebell (or dumbbell if you prefer) on the opposite side of the leg that’s working (contralateral) you’re resisting the force (KB/DB) pulling you away and down from the working side.

Adding in the rotation at the bottom (the eccentric portion) of the lift, your effort is  to resist the KB/DB’s line of travel.

What do you get? 

Anti-Rotation (how many planes are at work here?).
Slight increase in hip/glute work (I hate the word “activation”, btw).

I love this.  It’s the slightest variation but gives a hefty bang for your buck. 
As your ability increases, try to go heavier, more KB/Rotational velocity, don’t touch the ground with the KB/DB.

One more note:  push your hips forward when you stand up.  Do NOT arch your low back.  Remember the glutes work by extending the hip, so if you’re not standing up and extending the hip at the top, you’re leaving gains on the table.

It requires a thicker skin, purposely putting off quick and easy pleasure for goals you can only see down the road. It requires discipline and patience, belief in oneself and purposeful execution…

The Rear Delt / ALL upper back tings.

Mobility vs Stability

Knees are not meant to be mobile. 
Hips aren’t stable.

Ankles- mobile
Knees- stable
Hips- mobile
Lumbar spine- stable
Thoracic spine- mobile
Cervical spine- stable
Shoulder complex- mobile (with scapular stability)
Elbows- stable
Wrists- mobile

Start from the ground up. 
Not everything is a mobility issue and you don’t want to make a stable joint into a mobile joint- that’s heavy on the injury spectrum.

CRUSHED CANS

During the set up of a squat you need to remember that your trunk is like a soda can (yes I’m borrowing this analogy, don’t worry my ego isn’t big enough to believe I made this one up myself). When it’s upright and full it’s rigid, you can’t bend it in any direction because the pressure and structure is one unit. 
But, if you empty that can and bend or pinch in the sides, the whole thing becomes very unstable, not rigid and its weak AF.

Your trunk in the squat should look like a filled soda can. 

The video on the left shows that, my truck is rigid and therefore moving as a unit. With my ribs down it’s far easier to get and hold a bracing in the torso.  My knees start the movement (this is incredibly slight so look carefully - even then you may not see it). My go to cue - asshole to the ground as opposed to “butt back” or “hips to the wall”. 

The video on the right shows what an empty and pinched can would look like.  Notice the ribs flare up, hips shoot back and the entire torso becomes unstable, weak and working as separate parts - you’ll feel this in your squat because your erectors will work overtime (think stripper squats). Your eyes will shoot up to compensate for your low back being compressed and your hips cause a center of gravity shift & you may even notice that you push through your toes more than the whole foot (tripod) or heels.

If you’re a coach please STOP telling people to push their hips back or push through their heels.  Tell them to lower their ribs, start the movement with their knees and keep a neutral or lower than usual gaze. 

These couple shifts could save you from a back injury, pointless reps that won’t work your gluten or legs but will increase the load you are able to lift, the work your hip complex will get and some really fun PR days.

IT’S ALL CONNECTED

Everything in your body is connected.  There is not one tissue that is not connected to something that connects something else to another tissue. 

Why this is important to remember?  Well, when we think about injuries, often what can happen is that the injured side doesn’t feel as bad as the non injured side because the non injured side not only does what it’s supposed to do but it now compensates for what the injured side cannot do or won’t do.

The injured side also compensates and compounds the problems associated with the original injury.

Training your body so that all your parts are working together as a unit is fucking great.
Also training so that connections through your fascia lines are used as a team effort helps the body learn how to work together without compensation.

This can mean less compensation associated with injury, less injury because everything that works together is training to work together better.

Example:  your right glute is connected through fascial lines to your left shoulder.  What if you train them together and in coordinated movements?  Well, that’s a really strong unit.

Whatever you want to call this exercise is working opposing glute/shoulder actions.  A little awkward at first but incredibly helpful and challenging. 
Get creative with your exercises and think about lines of pull (how does this muscle contract and lengthen) and then consider the opposite action/muscle group you can connect with it.

Past or present injury

HOW HARD?

Did you know that current research is showing that a minimum of 10 hard HARD WORKING SETS per muscle group per week is necessary for growth?  It’s actually not that much but you better make sure it’s hard AF.

We had thought there was an upper limit to this but now it’s looking like as long as you can recover from what you’re doing, there may be no maximum number or working sets per muscle per week.

Although this is great research for us to base our training on, very few people truly know what HARD WORKING SETS are.

I’m not a proponent of taking each set to failure often but I am a ginormous fan of working at an intensity where you are left with only 2-ish reps in reserve per set. 
Most of my clients work sub maximally over months and then test at max when their training block is finished, however during those sub maximal weeks they should be working at no less than 85% of their ability , IMO.

Until someone truly knows the meaning of failure it may be hard for them to work at an intensity that feels ‘HARD’. 

So what do we really mean?  Does it mean sweating or being breathless?  Nah you can get that walking in a hot gym. 
A hard working set means that your muscle is fatiguing more than your muscles ability to perform more reps. 

If you can take less than a minute to recover from a set, you’re most likely not working hard enough and that’s going to delay your progress (regardless of your goal:  growth, fat loss, etc). 

Stop wasting your time and realize that this 60minutes you have should be the most taxing of your day.  Anything less than ‘hard’ is really just spinning your wheels. 

Show yourself ‘hard’ and take a couple sets to failure…. then show up for your next work out with a new perspective on what HARD WORKING SETS are.

NUANCE 

If you’re going to make fitness work for you then you’re going to have to get comfortable in the grey areas…

Areas that the texts books don’t cover. Like, if I can’t do what’s on my program, how do I get there with the equipment I have, the time I can commit, my abilities, etc. 
The text books will tell you do x,y,z.  But you may need to try m, n, o & p to make it work for you. 

And guess what?  It probably will, if you’re willing to try and experiment through it, committing to the process rather than the outcome.

The number of experiments I’ve been through in 20+ years of this thing we are calling ‘fitness’ is kind of wild.  I learned along the way what was text book perfect AND learned what was a workable process that would get me and my clients the same results.

Fitness is not black and white, it’s not “you can only do it x to get x result”. If it doesn’t work for you, move on and try something else. Otherwise you’re going to give up before you gave yourself a real chance.

You’ll find calculations everywhere for how to warm up, move up in weight and lose weight.  Math is easy.  Studies are easy to read but not always easy to apply.  That’s what makes the difference:  using the text book to make the real life process work. 

Get cozy in the grey areas. That’s where you’ll find what works for YOU!

Glutes

If you want the most out of your glute focused work, stop half assing it… literally.

Whether it’s hip thrusts or back extension, if you want your glutes to do the majority of the work:

Round the upper back
Tuck your chin to your chest.
Push your hips forward/under your rib cage, etc.

Your glutes move your hios so stop the half assed squats (neglecting to pull your hips forward), hip thrusts (laying your head back), step ups (failing to stand the fuck up). 

Rounding your back and tucking chin to chest will “turn off” your erectors (the low back) and encourage the glutes to do the work (ie contract fully aka shorten the muscle fibers), therefore: full ass booty work. 

A big booty is more than the motion, it’s the execution. 
If you’re going to be here, BE HERE! 

No half assed Ass work… mmmmk?

The basics

When do you get to stop doing the basics? 

Never fucking ever!

Get your protein.
Do your squats.
Ride the bike.

The foundation isn’t pulled away after the house is built.

And you shouldn’t pull yours just because you met your goal.

The basics are your foundation. 
Get good at them. 
Then get great at them.
Let them be second nature to you.

Then, build on em.

The boring basics…. Never stop em.

The #hack 

…is the work.

There is zero short cut… there is no easier way.

The work is required to get the result.

How do you do it?

165 was my personal best quite a while ago. I had a spotter and he, I’m pretty certain, damn near lifted 5-10% for me.

Fast forward to Sunday- this is that same load.
No spotter.
No real fear of being pinned.
My only fear was that my ass would be helping me too much. 
And I did it… twice

Here’s how:

Consistency to the stimulus. No program hopping, no random days. I kept working on the same movement patterns, the same monotonous work.

Worked on a variety of rep ranges and therefore loads.

Worked on the small details (like how to keep my body tight and quiet during the lift) and the big details (like keeping my body tight and quiet during the lift)- see what I did there?

I used progressive overload. Continuing to add difficulty (load, reps, tempo, pauses, etc) as previous stimulus got easier.

I wasn’t afraid to fail. I never use a spotter (the last PR bench attempt was my last spotter). I always work sub maximally. But I always work hard and to my safest limits.

I didn’t and won’t neglect accessory work. These are the lifts that bring up your weaknesses and are just as important as working on your main lifts, IMO. Do them! 

I’ve had injuries, and set backs, time away from the gym and everything in between. But I’ve shown up consistently for the work that requires me to continue progressing.
And I shift my perspective when necessary to continue making steps forward.

One of the most asked questions I get is:  What pre workout do you take? 

I annoys me to no end that the industry has somehow convinced people in order to have a good workout they need to have a pre workout powder and that somehow if you dry scoop it into your mouth you’ll have some euphoric experience in the weight room.

Stop it already.

What’s in a pre-workout anyways? From a current very well known supplement company who will remain nameless because I think their stuff is over priced and fairly BS:
B6, B12, Choline, Magnesium, Sodium, Potassium, L Tyrosine, Maltodextrin, Caffeine, Coffee Fruit Extract, Black Pepper Extract, Hyperzine-A, Citric Acid, Natural & Artificial Flavors, Malic Acid, Silicon Dioxide, Sucralose, Ace-K & A whole bunch of fruit extracts.

Want to know what’s in my @YETI every morning when I workout? 
BLACK COFFEE.  Straight up no powder, no funky flavors trying to mimic your favorite alcoholic beverage, no names like “Dragon Unicorn Extreme Death Pump Pre”, no beaver anus extract (seriously, check out where they get berry flavors from), no proprietary blends that are a secret to you the consumer.
It’s literally drip coffee (@sarahschollathlete ‘s LumberJacked from @weirdbroscoffee - best I’ve found!).

I do not care what the hell kind of magic sauce is in your funky can/powder/bag of pre workout - it’s an over priced mix of nothing that you can’t get from a banana, salt and coffee when it comes to getting a sick pump and/or energy to power you through your session. 

Experiment with food sources that aid in your energy and desired pump (salty tortilla chips work well for me and were a pre stage food when I competed).

I haven’t taken a pre workout supplement in probably 20 years…. so what makes you think you have to? 
Save your money, save your skin being itchy as fuck and distracting, save your potential reactions to proprietary blends. 

Now go have a good workout.

The box

Have you put yourself inside a fitness box? 

Telling yourself that if you can’t get to the gym, you can’t get in shape? 
If you can’t run 5miles, what’s the point in working out? 
Went off the rails with your nutrition one night so now there is no point in tracking your macros… ever? 

I call bullshit. 
There are so many ways to get “fit”, “healthy”, “in shape”.

The reason your not may be because you’ve put yourself in a self imposed box and are now comfortable there… the only problem is that you’re actually not comfortable at all… you’re just not uncomfortable enough to break out of your little proverbial  prison cell.

The gym, the specific exercise, the tracking macros (any diet for that matter) is simply a tool, not a rule.

If the imposing block is out of your control, you still have massive control over other things- like yourself! 
If the thing that is stopping you from your goals is you… well, I’ve got great news, you control you and you can absolutely do some epic shit if you are willing.

All problems have solutions and the best solution isn’t always the one that’s most obvious (gym=fit). Sometimes working your way around the problem is exactly what you need to solve it (lifting concrete blocks, calisthenics, swimming protein > more pasta. And no, pasta isn’t bad for you unless you have other issues… ok? OK?!?).

The box you put yourself in only limits you to the point you decide to be limit-less. 

Get out of your box.

I built this shit. 
This is the fullest my back has been in a while and thanks to peanut butter chocolate cheerios, jasmine rice, allllllll the proteins and fats, good and consistent work and mmmmmm creatine, it’s coming together a ok! 

Losing weight and being shredded isn’t the only progress to be proud of.  Be proud of building the foundation, the muscle, the body that comes before the bikini bod.
Take some time and realize what you’re building right now! It’s hard work and taxes the mind as well as the body. 

So if you’re out here building something that isn’t quite what you’re wanting but you’re still working, being consistent and staying the course… I see you! I’m proud of you and hope you’re proud of you! 

That is all.

CHILL ALREADY

•I weighed myself last night before bed. I indulged heavily all day. 168.6
Then I weighed myself this morning (been pretty consistent between 162.4-163.2 every morning). 163.4

•Too often people weigh themselves at the time of day that is the WORST time to weigh (night) and freak out about the scale moving up through the day or over a couple days when they’ve been eating more or less”off” their plan/macros.

•First of all, your body CANNOT store this much fat that fast. 
By that logic I would have dropped pure fat while I slept for 6 hours last night and that’s fucking impossible as well.

•The scale is a tool, not the judge. The scale is a representation of gravity’s pull on your body. The more mass that body has the more pull toward the earth (basic shit right here guys). So if I eat 10lbs of food in a day, I will have more mass at the end of that day because of the mass that I stuffed into me, not because it magically converted to fat and stored itself as such. 

•The body has processes it goes through to store and burn fat. A day or two during the holidays isn’t going to trigger a massive physiological response. Continue the gluttony through January and yes, you’re going to see some semi permanent fat gain on the scale. But these few weeks during the holiday? Meh. Your body LOVES homeostasis (being the same) and a few days of over eating will likely just make your body work a little harder to not gain weight (check the thermic effect of food).

•Know that you’ll gain WATER weight because the body loves water and will pull water into the body’s cells and does so much more easily with carbohydrates and salt (don’t avoid these at all, just know they have an effect on storing water in the body!).

•Is the scale going to actually stop you from indulging? Probably not. This behavior is mental, not physiological (miss me with “starvation mode” theory). So unless you’re going to see the scale and actually get shit on track, stop stressing about it and move on: control your controllables (water intake, movement, hit your daily protein goals).

This was a simple back day today, but it was SO nice to not have pain, to be moving with far less restriction.
Im celebrating & stacking small wins… that’s when the big wins start!

One of my Favorites

Our older generation is one of my favorite populations to train, For multiple reasons.

But probably the biggest reason is the wisdom they have and will share. I have learned so much from just listening to my older clients. 
We train hard and per their goals and progress in those directions will always happen, but honestly, they don’t even know, I probably get more out of our sessions than they will.

Diane, shown, wants to continue being able to travel, walk wherever she finds herself on the globe and generally continue her very fulfilling life. That’s goal #1.
Goal #2 (usually my goal for my client) is to help her move BETTER than when she came to me.

She was dealing with a very unstable SI and needing “adjustments” often. 
Since starting to work together in November ‘23 she’s had no adjustments and her back hasn’t bothered her on her road trips/travel. 

It’s been fun to watch her strength increase, pain subside, listen to her experiences and be a part of it all.

Just a little insight into my world for ya.

Failure in Lifting

It doesn’t mean you are moving backward. 
It means you are taxing your muscle fibers to the extent (if done correctly and consistently in a manner that does not promote injury or over training)  they are forced to adapt. 
Adaptation = growth. 
The process to growth means over stimulating.
Failure is over stimulating. 

Today I pressed 95# for 3x3 after pyramiding up to that weight with appropriate rep schemes relative to the weight being pushed. 

Presses and (L) raises are where I’m going to try to fail on shoulder day.  I want those muscle fibers to grow and I’ll use accessories post presses & (L) Raises to incur the most amount of taxation possible. 
So, no failing on every lift, just the ones you want the most adaptation from.

Understanding your goals and abilities per the muscle group you are trying to grow (yes, ladies, if you want to ‘lose weight’, look fitter or any of the above, you want to GROW your meat bundles - ie muscles) will help you know where to go to failure.

Failure doesn’t mean moving backward.

You need less than you think

Remember the gym is to stimulate, not annihilate.

6-8 exercises. 3-5 working sets of each.
Bam!

Sure, I often go over these numbers- I’m a woman and therefore typically will handle higher amounts of volume better than comparable men.

The trick is being able to recover (where the growth happens) from the work done.

I find more often than not, people need higher volume because they don’t truly understand what WORK is…. Let’s not get started on true failure. 

Too often when I ask a client “was that heavy?” They respond: “it was good”, or “heavy enough”.
Well, no, if that was good, then it’s not heavy enough. 

Lean into working hard here,  into being unsure if you’ll complete the set and get excited about making it harder as soon as it becomes easier.

This is my session from today. Turns out I am sick, so it’s a little less than typical but please note it’s not 30 exercises.

Warm Up: 5’ comfortable pace on the bike, Lat stretch, hip openers.

SSB Squat 4x10 @ 120
Bulgarians 3x20 ea w/30’s
DB Hip Thrusts 4x20 w/90
Copenhagen planks 3x20”ea
Weighted Deadbug w/heal tap3x30” ea

The trick is to use a load that makes you work hard enough that another set sounds kinda gross. My lower body has always been my weakest, but I work hard because it’s relative.

Don’t get caught up in the BS. 
Hit what you need to grow. 
Recover like a mother fucker. 
Get better.

What I do when I’m sick

It happens.  We catch something and it’s a few days of feeling like hot garbage. 
Don’t worry, your gains and progress are not lost.  Here’s what I do:
Determine whether it’s a good idea to go to the gym.  Above the chest, no need to rest.  Chest and down, stay home.
Cranial/sinus pressure can make lifting unbearable (🙋🏼‍♀️). No need to lift in these conditions.

I rest.  A few days of not training and getting needed rest is better than prolonging the healing by getting half ass sessions done.  I cancelled clients, took naps, and took care of myself rather than pushing limits.

I eat my protein.  Don’t neglect nutrition just because of a virus (unless you’re puking). Sprinkle in carbs and fats as desired.
And don’t be reluctant to increase calories.  The  body is trying to fight off a threat, why wouldn’t i give it the energy it needs to fight harder and better? 

WATER, WATER, WATER.  Holy shit, drink water. Tea and water have been constant for me. Will I gain some water weight this week? Yep. Am I gonna cry about, absofuckinlutely not.

Movement as able. The last couple days for me have been on the couch mostly, just letting my body rest.  Walking if not light headed, stretching and today maybe some light strength training (glute bridges, body weight work, walking) but only maybe.

I take some Elderberry syrup, load up on vitamin C & D (less sun means more supplementing here).

I use my red light and if able, sit in hot and cold baths. 

And finally, I’m not feeling guilty about not training, or training less.  What will that actually do for me?  Letting my body rest, recover and heal is, in the moment, priority.

I’ll feel softer and a little heavy when it all breaks.
This is another reason I choose to stay consistent 95% of the time… so this 5% doesn’t affect me and it quickly passed.

I’m starting a new trend.

It’s called: do the step mill without doing any stupid kick back, band around the legs, side stepping or other bullshit nonsense.

I can guaran-fucking-tee that you’ll get as good a result, if not better, by just stepping on the damn thing.  Go faster, go slower.  Believe it or not IT FUCKING WORKS!

It’s getting ridiculous that people think every cotton picking exercise has to be changed for some special reason (usually to target the glutes… boring!). 

Believe me, the step mill isn’t going to get you the badonkadonk you’re after.  Yes, it will help, but it’s really there for a cardiovascular affect, not muscle building.  So use it for cardio, burn those calories, pump that heart… but don’t you dare think that doing weird shit on it is going to grow your ass some special way. 

You can use other machinery/implements with some flair and get cool results, but please leave the step mill alone.

Also, I pulled an ‘influencer’ move… I finished my cardio, then set up my phone to record a few minutes of stepping.  It felt gross to do, but I’m taking one for the team here so you can actually make progress. 
So, now that I’ve done the unthinkable - this should go viral, right? 

RIGHT?
